title: Aftermath of the Birth of Republic
subtitle: How shall we react to the unfolding events?
view-if: year = 1931 and month = 4 and fortnight = 2
on-arrival: president_catalonia == "Macia"
new-page: true
max-visits: 1
face-image: img/portraits/SchleicherKurt.jpg
tags: event

  The Catalan Republican Left has decided to fold after lengthy negotiations with the other Republican parties and promises of autonomy, also extended to the Basque and Galician minorities and their parties.
  The proclamation of the Second Spanish Republic is big news for us and all of Spain. We have played our part in the Dictatorship's fall and on occasions we have had our moments of shared struggle and persecution with the Republican parties. For that reason, several representatives and voices in the editor's committee of Solidaridad Obrera, led by Joan Peiro, have proposed we express our enthusiasm of the Republican triumph and our hopes for fruitfull partnership with our Republican allies. Many representatives in the National Committee from the reformist and unionist wings support Peiro's proposal since we too have played our part in the fall of the dictatorship and the monarchy.
  
  On the other hand, the anarchist firebrands who were recently freed after the amnesty and some of whom have returned from exile, will not hesitate to oppose the Republic and denounce it as a bourgoise oppressor. Their fiery rhetoric will surely sway the more radical members of the union and maybe Sr. Peiro's proposal wouldn't, strictly speaking, represent the vast majority of the workers in the union.

  What course of action does the editorial committee take? Do they share in the popular celebrations? Or are they swayed to denounce the newborn state as a defender of capitalist exploters and yet another vessel of reaction?
  
